text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Expansion: Do cartoons really impact people's persepective%0a:Author: sathyas%0a:Original: [[Articles.AccentDiscriminationAgainstAsiansInMedia|AccentDiscriminationAgainstAsiansInMedia]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.ShahinC|ShahinC]]%0a:Section: E%0a:Completed: 02.05.2021 - 20:40%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210511-223422-423910#%0a* [-11.05.2021 - 15:34-] || TA_mason marked as complete%0a#foxend 210511-223422-423910#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aOne idea I am curious about is whether people's perspective of Indians is really effected by the cartoon and Apu's accent. Another similar situation is the many instances when legislation attempted to ban violent video games as a means of stopping violence. But do violent video games really cause people to be more violent?%0a%0aI explored on Youtube and google to learn about Indian people's sentiment towards Apu and the stereotypes regarding his character. In the video clip, I found that roughly 2/3 of the people interviewed were not offended or found it funny themselves, and 1/3 seemed mildly offended. They explain that they understand that it is a cartoon and large part of humor is making fun of certain aspects of people. Some even agreed that the depiction of the accent, arranged marriages, and dowries were not totally unrealistic albeit exaggerated.%0a%0aSidharth Bhatia, Mumbai-based founder-editor of The Wire said that, "It (Apu) reflects true American diversity. The controversy about the stereotyping is classist snobbery - Indians in America don't want to be reminded of a certain kind of immigrant from their country - the shop keepers, the taxi drivers, the burger flippers". He explains how the small group of Indian-Americans would rather focus on "Silicon Valley successes, the Wall Street players and the Ivy League products" but in reality there are millions of Apu's in America.%0a%0ahttps://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-44027613%0ahttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cJb77ggFgTE%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a(:GradedBy: TA_mason:)
